## Common Mistakes

- Over-reliance on AI suggestions without understanding the generated code - AI can produce syntactically correct but semantically flawed code that introduces subtle bugs
- Not configuring privacy settings properly - AI plugins may send code to external servers; ensure sensitive code (API keys, proprietary algorithms) is protected
- Accepting inline suggestions without reviewing context - suggestions may use outdated APIs, deprecated patterns, or conflict with existing project conventions
- Ignoring licensing implications - AI-generated code may inadvertently reproduce training data under unexpected licenses; always review for compliance
- Using plugins without API key security - storing API keys in plain text configuration files can expose credentials; use environment variables instead
- Assuming AI understands project context perfectly - large projects with complex architecture may confuse models; provide explicit context through comments and file references
- Not updating plugin configurations for different projects - using the same settings across projects with different tech stacks leads to suboptimal suggestions
- Neglecting to verify AI-generated security-sensitive code - plugins may suggest code with vulnerabilities, especially in authentication and data handling routines


## Best Practices

- Always review AI-generated code before committing, especially for security-sensitive operations, critical business logic, and external API interactions
- Use multi-model approaches strategically: Copilot for fast inline completions, Cline for complex refactoring tasks, specialized tools for domain-specific needs
- Configure privacy boundaries explicitly: use .gitignore patterns, comment blocks with #exclude-from-ai, or plugin-specific exclusion settings for sensitive files
- Develop consistent commenting patterns that help AI understand your intent: clear function descriptions, type hints, and architectural context improve suggestions
- Maintain separate configurations per project when dealing with diverse tech stacks - a React project and a Python data science project benefit from different settings
- Build regular verification into your workflow: review AI suggestions during PR reviews, run tests after accepting suggestions, and track which patterns cause issues
- Stay informed about plugin updates and new capabilities - the AI tooling landscape evolves rapidly, and features that were limitations may be addressed in updates
- Use AI as a learning tool: when AI suggests unfamiliar patterns, research them thoroughly to expand your knowledge rather than blindly accepting suggestions

